BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC State Gregg Museum of Art & Design
CATEGORIES:Exhibitions
DESCRIPTION:The House of Ideas: Plants in Art will be on exhibit in the Cab
 aniss Gallery in the Historic Chancellor’s Residence every Tuesday-Saturday
  until May 31\, 2026. This exhibition is a participatory learning lab that 
 uncovers the artistic representation of plants in our lives and in the natu
 ral world. It features objects from the Gregg Museum of Art & Design Collec
 tion that depict the roles of plants from nourishment and communal living t
 o the scientific study of human health. The House of Ideas offers a relaxin
 g room for botanical sketching and a self-guided tour of the museum’s garde
 n.
DTEND:20260303T220000Z
DTSTAMP:20260327T030132Z
DTSTART:20260303T150000Z
GEO:35.784762;-78.661636
LOCATION:Gregg Museum of Art & Design\, Cabaniss Gallery
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:The House of Ideas: Plants in Art Exhibition
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_50392730685699
URL:https://calendar.ncsu.edu/event/the-house-of-ideas-plants-in-art
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC State Gregg Museum of Art & Design
CATEGORIES:Community Events,Exhibitions
DESCRIPTION:Come to the Gregg Museum of Art & Design for an evening gallery
  walkthrough with the curatorial and collections teams. We will explore the
  exhibition Through Our Eyes\, In Our Hands: Prioritizing Indigenous Knowle
 dge in Museums. This exhibit foregrounds Native perspectives on the steward
 ship of cultural belonging and the histories and futures of repatriation. T
 hrough Indigenous voices and frameworks\, the exhibition reframes long-held
  museum practices\, asking visitors to consider questions of authority\, ow
 nership\, knowledge and care.\n\nLee Chavis-Tartaglia\, the Native American
  Graves Protection and Repatriation Act (NAGPRA) collections assistant\, an
 d Meredith Osborne\, a curatorial assistant\, will offer insight into the s
 ignificance of the NAGPRA. They will also share archival materials\, person
 al accounts\, community-based narratives in the exhibition and the process 
 of developing the exhibition from start to finish.
DTEND:20260305T230000Z
DTSTAMP:20260327T030132Z
DTSTART:20260305T220000Z
GEO:35.784762;-78.661636
LOCATION:Gregg Museum of Art & Design\, Front Lobby
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Prioritizing Indigenous Knowledge in Museums
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51949067080542
URL:https://calendar.ncsu.edu/event/a-closer-look-museum-staff-unpack-throu
 gh-our-eyes-in-our-hands-prioritizing-indigenous-knowledge-in-museums
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC State Gregg Museum of Art & Design
CATEGORIES:Lectures and Talks,Community Events
DESCRIPTION:National Identity\, Provenance\, and the Global Politics of Res
 titution\nJoin the Gregg Museum of Art & Design in a timely\, cross-discipl
 inary conversation about art\, provenance\, cultural and national identity\
 , and the global politics of restitution. Professor Jelena Subotic is a Dis
 tinguished University Professor of Political Science at Georgia State Unive
 rsity\, specializing in International Relations\, cultural heritage\, memor
 y politics\, and state identity. She is the author of The Art of Status: Lo
 oted Treasures and the Global Politics of Restitution (Oxford University Pr
 ess\, 2025). Dr. Sandra van Ginhoven is Head of the Getty Provenance Index\
 , where she spearheaded a significant redesign of the Index making it easie
 r for museums and researchers to use. The revamped Index permits telling de
 epened stories of museum collections. The conversation is in conjunction wi
 th the exhibition Through Our Eyes\, In Our Hands: Prioritizing Indigenous 
 Knowledge in Museums on view now at the Gregg Museum. This exhibit centers 
 Native perspectives on museum stewardship\, repatriation\, and cultural aut
 hority.\n\n \n\nThis program is co-hosted by the Department of Political Sc
 ience and Department of History.\n\n \n\nThis event is free\, but registrat
 ion is required. Please RSVP here.
DTEND:20260307T000000Z
DTSTAMP:20260327T030132Z
DTSTART:20260306T223000Z
GEO:35.784762;-78.661636
LOCATION:Gregg Museum of Art & Design\, Main Lobby
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:National Identity\, Provenance\, and the Global Politics of Restitu
 tion
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52142685852037
URL:https://calendar.ncsu.edu/event/national-identity-provenance-and-the-gl
 obal-politics-of-restitution
END:VEVENT
